ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, we designed an intelligent core–shell nanoplatform (PEGylated AIPH@MSN/CDs-MnO2, denoted as A@M/C-Mn) for TME-responsive synergistic diagnosis and phototherapy against hypoxic tumors (Fig. 1
                     ). Amine-functionalized mesoporous silica nanoparticle (MSN) serves as a carrier that not only enables high encapsulation of AIPH but also facilitate the loading of photosensitive carbon dots (CDs) through electrostatic interactions. A redox reaction occurred following KMnO4 treatment, leading to the formation of MnO2 NS, which effectively protects the sealed CDs and AIPH. Finally, the nanoplatform was PEGylated to enhance biocompatibility and prolong blood circulation time. Once internalized by tumor cells, the outer-layer MnO2 NS can catalyze endogenous H2O2 to produce O2, thereby ameliorating hypoxic atmosphere. Concurrently, the formation of O2 and release of Mn2+ could generate US/MR imaging signals, enabling the monitoring of nanoplatform distribution in vivo. This process also facilitates the recovery of FL from quenched CDs and the release of encapsulated AIPH for therapeutic purposes. Additionally, PA and FL imaging performance of CDs provide enhanced contrast and spatial resolution. Upon NIR laser irradiation, the in situ O2 supply accelerates the formation of singlet oxygen (1O2) for enhanced O2-dependent PDT by CDs. The simultaneously generated local hyperthermia not only enables PTT but also promotes the rapid release and decomposition of encapsulated AIPH, generating O2-independent free radicals (

                     R). This dual action overcomes PDT resistance, achieving co-enhanced synergistic PDT/PTT. Furthermore, the biocompatibility and therapeutic efficacy of A@M/C-Mn, guided by tetra-modal imaging of FL, US, MR, and PA, were demonstrated both in vitro and in vivo. Therefore, this study highlights the potential of A@M/C-Mn as an effective nanoplatform for boosting synergistic PDT/PTT in hypoxic TME.
